post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_30929941_30929971_0": {"length": 26, "quality": 0.9285714285714286, "section_id": 5907}}, "n3337": {"so_30929941_30929971_0": {"length": 26, "quality": 0.9285714285714286, "section_id": 5679}}, "n4659": {"so_30929941_30929971_0": {"length": 24, "quality": 0.8571428571428571, "section_id": 7389}}}, "30929971": {"Id": "30929971", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Because it isn't a definition. Static data members must be defined outside the class definition.</p>\n<p>[class.static.data] / 2</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_30929941_30929971_0\">The declaration of a <code>static</code> data member in its class definition <strong>is not\n  a definition</strong> and may be of an incomplete type other than cv-qualified\n  <code>void</code>. The definition for a <code>static</code> data member shall appear in a\n  namespace scope enclosing the member\u2019s class definition.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>As for taking the address of your static member without actually defining it, it will compile, but it shouldn't link.</p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "657267", "LastActivityDate": "2015-06-19T05:16:29.213", "Score": "2", "CreationDate": "2015-06-19T04:36:38.307", "ParentId": "30929941", "CommentCount": "3", "OwnerUserId": "657267", "LastEditDate": "2015-06-19T05:16:29.213"}, "30929967": {"Id": "30929967", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>you need to put a definition of <code>NumTurns</code> in source file, like</p>\n<pre><code>const int GamePlayer::NumTurns;\n</code></pre>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2015-06-19T04:36:28.620", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2015-06-19T04:36:28.620", "ParentId": "30929941", "Score": "1", "OwnerUserId": "700650"}, "30929941": {"ViewCount": "230", "Body": "<p>I'm reading Scott Meyers' C++ and come across this example:</p>\n<pre><code>class GamePlayer{\nprivate:\n    static const int NumTurns = 5;\n    int scores[NumTurns];\n    // ...\n};\n</code></pre>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_30929941_30929941_0\">What you see above is a declaration for <code>NumTurns</code>, not a definition.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Why not a definition? It looks like we initialize the static data member with 5.</p>\n<p>I just don't understand what it means to declare but <strong>not define</strong> a variable with the value 5. We can take the address of the variable fine.</p>\n<pre><code>class A\n{\npublic:\n    void foo(){ const int * p = &amp;a; }\nprivate:\n    static const int a = 1;\n};\n\nint main ()\n{\n    A a;\n    a.foo();\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p><a href=\"http://coliru.stacked-crooked.com/a/bef630a515bba5b2\" rel=\"nofollow\">DEMO</a></p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "30929971", "Title": "Definition of the static data member", "CreationDate": "2015-06-19T04:33:41.963", "Id": "30929941", "CommentCount": "2", "LastEditDate": "2015-06-19T05:14:14.320", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "241631", "LastActivityDate": "2015-06-19T05:16:29.213", "Score": "2", "OwnerUserId": "2786156", "Tags": "<c++><static-members>", "AnswerCount": "2"}});